# AgentWorld

AgentWorld is a revival of an old Java Swing university assignment: an
"Agents in a Grid World" simulation with plants, simple creatures, intelligent
creatures, energy, memory, communication, and pair cooperation.

The original Java source is preserved in `AgentWorld/src` and copied under
`legacy/AgentWorld/src`. The old root README is preserved as
`legacy/README-original`.

## Current Status

Milestone 1 is implemented:

- migration report from the Java code and README,
- Vite + React + TypeScript scaffold,
- deterministic TypeScript simulation core with no React/DOM/rendering imports,
- centralized simulation config,
- seeded randomness,
- serializable world state,
- Classic Mode baseline rules for plants, energy, inventory, combinations,
  Intel memory, communication, and pair partnerships,
- Vitest coverage for the core simulation.

The browser shell now includes start/pause, step, reset, mode switching, creature
and plant insertion, clear actions, expanded Classic tuning controls for energy,
inventory, memory, plant rewards, combo rewards, exact simple/intel population
controls with live counters, legacy-style plant population watchers and active
pair counters in the side panel, debug/memory/link overlays, explicit energy
overlays for quick hunger reads, quick default-reset presets for Classic,
Advanced, and overlay tuning, collapsible control sections with live summaries, selected creature
drill-down with world-aware hunger/target/visibility diagnostics, in-panel
linked-creature jump controls, and a live creature roster, a PixiJS Classic Mode renderer with
selected/visible/target cell debug highlighting, plant and creature memory cell
overlays, selected-creature trail/facing overlays, fertility heatmap, creature
energy badges, and intel intent beams, persistent selected-cell inspection with
stacked-creature quick-select controls in both the viewport and selected-creature
side panel, cell hover inspection, a side-panel event log driven by
deterministic snapshot diffs plus communication transcripts for shares,
partnerships, and advanced group join/leave events, JSON snapshot capture/load for deterministic debug
sessions, advanced terrain/season/memory-decay controls, seasonal plant energy
variation, fertility-weighted Advanced Mode spawning, advanced intel strategy
controls for cooperation/exploration/exploitation/risk/memory/reserve tuning,
advanced bounded group-size tuning for intel leaders,
and an initial Three.js Advanced Mode scene, plus deterministic intel
communication transcripts that are serialized into snapshots and surfaced in
the selected-creature side panel. The shell now also exposes the live plant-set
batch size and intel partnership threshold, and the selected-creature panel
shows current group IDs, group membership, and partnership thresholds for
tuning/debugging, plus target-actionability summaries and visible-cell
inspection rows for quicker Classic pursuit debugging. Pinned cells now act as
scenario staging points, with direct controls to spawn simple/intel creatures
or exact plant colors into the inspected square for deterministic reproduction,
plus per-cell clear/remove actions and selected-creature energy nudges/removal
for faster deterministic scenario editing.
The Classic viewport inspector now also reports selected-creature context per
cell, including previous/ahead/linked flags, remembered plant or creature
entries in that square, and intel targeters currently pursuing it. Advanced 3D
zoom stays clear at wider camera distances, and the event log is constrained to
an internal scrolling panel so new events do not move the grid viewport. The app
now sits inside a `sarathchandra.com` site frame with home/navigation backlinks,
a subtle AgentWorld watermark, and a personal-project disclaimer matching the
main site's restrained Ghost-style theme. The Pixi Classic cell inspector also
supports the same pinned-cell edit actions as the side panel, so viewport-first
debugging can add/remove plants and creatures without leaving the board.

## Run

```bash
npm install
npm run dev
```

## Test

```bash
npm test
npm run typecheck
npm run lint
```

The full local production gate is:

```bash
npm run check
```

The npm scripts use Vite/Vitest's native config loader, and Vitest runs on the
thread pool so the standard commands stay compatible with sandboxed Windows
environments where child-process spawning is restricted.

## GitHub Actions CI

GitHub Actions runs on pushes and pull requests to `master`. The workflow uses
Node.js 24, installs dependencies with `npm ci`, runs the same local production
gate via `npm run check`, validates the Hostinger Docker Compose config, builds
the production Docker image with `AGENTWORLD_BASE=/agentworld/`, and smoke-tests
the mounted app plus `llms.txt` and `ai-index.json`.

Deployment to the VPS is still controlled by the Hostinger update script below.
That keeps production changes explicit until a later deploy workflow is wired to
GitHub environment secrets.

## Production Deployment

Build and serve only the static `dist/` output on public infrastructure. Do not
expose `npm run dev`, Vite preview, Node, npm, or the Docker API to the public
internet.

```bash
docker build -t agentworld:prod .
docker run --rm -p 8080:8080 agentworld:prod
```

For a path deployment such as `https://www.sarathchandra.com/agentworld/`,
build with:

```bash
AGENTWORLD_BASE=/agentworld/ npm run build
```

or pass the same base path into the Docker build:

```bash
docker build --build-arg AGENTWORLD_BASE=/agentworld/ -t agentworld:prod .
```

The included Nginx config serves both `/` and `/agentworld/` so the same image
can be tested locally while still supporting the planned site path.

### Hostinger VPS Recommended Path

For `https://www.sarathchandra.com/agentworld/`, use the Hostinger Docker VPS
template or any Ubuntu VPS with Docker Compose:

```bash
ssh root@YOUR_VPS_IP
git clone https://github.com/chathura77/agentworldv2.git /opt/agentworld
cd /opt/agentworld
cp deploy/hostinger/.env.example deploy/hostinger/.env
docker compose --env-file deploy/hostinger/.env -f deploy/hostinger/compose.yaml up -d --build
```

The Compose service binds the app to `127.0.0.1:8080` only. Add
`deploy/hostinger/nginx-agentworld-location.conf` to the existing HTTPS Nginx
server block for `sarathchandra.com`, then run:

```bash
nginx -t
systemctl reload nginx
```

Update later with:

```bash
APP_DIR=/opt/agentworld /opt/agentworld/deploy/hostinger/update.sh
```

For full first-deploy, update, optional timer, subdomain, firewall, and rollback
notes, see `docs/hostinger-vps-deployment.md`. See also
`docs/production-readiness.md` and `docs/security-review.md` for the public
VM/container checklist and security review.

## SEO and AI Indexing

The static shell includes canonical metadata for
`https://www.sarathchandra.com/agentworld/`, Open Graph/Twitter cards,
Schema.org JSON-LD, a sitemap, robots rules, and a no-JavaScript fallback summary
so crawlers can understand the project before the React simulation loads.

Machine-readable resources for AI assistants and retrieval systems are published
from `public/`:

- `llms.txt`: concise LLM-oriented project summary and preferred citation.
- `agentworld.md`: fuller Markdown brief for AI agents and answer engines.
- `ai-index.json`: structured facts about modes, concepts, resources, and runtime
  behavior.

If this app is mounted under the main Ghost site at `/agentworld/`, make sure the
root `sarathchandra.com/robots.txt` or main sitemap links to
`https://www.sarathchandra.com/agentworld/sitemap.xml`.

## Classic Mode Mapping

Classic Mode follows the original Java behavior where practical:

- the default 500x500 Java world maps to a 5x5 cell grid,
- plants are replenished to a target population in sets of up to four,
- plant energy defaults are green `100`, red `50`, yellow `70`, magenta `90`,
- combo values are green+red `450`, yellow+red `420`, magenta+yellow `400`,
- SimpleCreature has same-square plant vision, hunger eating, inventory limits,
  random movement, and separate moving/staying energy costs,
- IntelCreature adds memory, current/ahead observation, target pursuit,
  communication, shared combinations, and leader/partner cooperation.

Known Java bugs are documented in `docs/migration-report.md`. The TypeScript
Classic Mode intentionally fixes the square-change energy comparison bug and the
Intel observation range precedence bug because both contradict the README and
source comments.

## Advanced Mode

Advanced Mode can be toggled in the shell without resetting the world. It now
switches the presentation into a Three.js 3D environment with terrain, lighting,
camera controls, 3D plant/agent meshes, relationship beams, memory markers,
fertility heat tiles, intel intent beams, and selected-creature debug path cues.
The core now also includes deterministic fertility maps when enabled, seasonal
spawn weighting and plant-energy variation, configurable memory confidence
decay, utility-scored intel target selection, terrain-aware pursuit routing, and
serialized communication transcripts for share and partnership actions. Advanced
strategy weights now let the shell tune how aggressively intel creatures prefer
partnerships, scouting, remembered targets, risky routes, and energy reserve.
Advanced leaders can now recruit bounded multi-creature groups that trail behind
the leader and dissolve deterministically when the shared task ends.
Remaining planned additions are
covered in `docs/advanced-mode-design.md`:

- terrain and fertility,
- seasonal resource variation,
- memory confidence decay,
- pathfinding and utility scoring,
- richer communication,
- bounded leader-managed groups,
- personality/strategy weights,
- visual overlays and camera controls.

## Known Limitations

- Advanced Mode uses an early Three.js renderer and remains functional rather
  than final art quality.
- Grid-size changes currently reset the world.
- Advanced Mode pathfinding now reacts to fertility, but richer communication
  beyond join/leave and partnership messages is still pending.
- The old Java thread interleavings are not reproduced exactly; the new core is
  deterministic by design.

## Future Ideas

- Multi-creature groups with leader task selection and reward splitting.
- Personality-driven pathfinding and ecological feedback loops.
